SubTopics: Analyze how point of view and/or author purpose shapes the content and style of diverse texts.
Content: How does the narrator's point of view affect the reader's understanding of the text?

A.Choice: The narrator's objective retelling of the events conveys an anxious, almost frightful tone.

B.Choice: The narrator's reflective manner assures the reader that the story will have a cheerful outcome.

C.Choice: The narrator's incredible descriptions give the reader a sense of his confusion at what was happening.

D.Choice: The narrator's use of exaggeration creates a mood of skepticism about whether the event really occurred.

SubTopics: Write narrative fiction or literary nonfiction to convey experiences and/or events using effective techniques, well-chosen details, and well-structured event sequences.
Content: At the end of the passage, the author creates suspense about what the narrator will do. Write a multi-paragraph continuation of the story that describes what happens next. Be sure to use what you have learned about the setting, characters, and plot of the passage.

:ibox:Manage your time carefully so that you can:

• plan your story and do some prewriting using the resources provided.

• write your narrative.
Your written response should be in the form of a multi-paragraph narrative.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which sentence BEST expresses a central idea of passage 1?

A.Choice: The artist Basil Hallward is so entranced with a portrait he has painted that he does not want to put it on public display.

B.Choice: Lord Henry, a patron of the arts, tries to persuade the artist Basil Hallward to change the gallery he works with.

C.Choice: Basil Hallward's earlier disappearance from London had caused a great deal of excitement in the city.

D.Choice: Basil Hallward risks his professional reputation by insisting that his work not be displayed.

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: How do Lord Henry's feelings toward Basil Hallward change by the end of passage 1?

M.Choice: He is jealous of Basil's abilities at first but begins to pity the lonely painter by the end.

P.Choice: He admires Basil's fine work at the beginning but becomes confused by his strange behavior.

R.Choice: He has little interest in Basil when he arrives but comes to wonder at his magnificent talent.

S.Choice: He is worried about Basil at the beginning but becomes hopeful after speaking with his friend.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
Which sentence BEST expresses a central idea of passage 2?

M.Choice: A scientist suffers delusions from long periods of solitude.

P.Choice: A creator feels an unexpected revulsion for his creation.

R.Choice: An ordinary man represses his human emotions in a sterile, scientific environment.

S.Choice: An inventor persists in pursuing his goal despite criticism from peers.

Content: Which quotation from the passage BEST supports the correct answer to Part A?

A.Choice: “With an anxiety that almost amounted to agony, I collected the instruments of life around me, that I might infuse a spark of being into the lifeless thing that lay at my feet.” (paragraph 8)

B.Choice: “His limbs were in proportion, and I had selected his features as beautiful.” (paragraph 9)

C.Choice: “The different accidents of life are not so changeable as the feelings of human nature.” (paragraph 10)

D.Choice: “I had desired it with an ardour that far exceeded moderation; but now that I had finished, the beauty of the dream vanished, and breathless horror and disgust filled my heart.” (paragraph 10)

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
In passage 2, which statement characterizes the narrator's reaction to his creation?

M.Choice: He is surprised that his feelings about his creation have changed so quickly.

P.Choice: Regardless of his horror, he remains proud of his accomplishment.

R.Choice: In spite of himself, he feels loyal to his creature.

S.Choice: He realizes that he has sacrificed companionship for his creation.

Content: Select the phrase from paragraph 10 that BEST supports the correct answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “... I had deprived myself of rest and health.”

B.Choice: “... the beauty of the dream vanished, ...”

D.Choice: “... I rushed out of the room and continued a long time traversing my bed- chamber, ...”

SubTopics: Analyze how complex characters, events, and ideas develop and interact over the course of a text to impact meaning.
Content: What do the main characters in the two passages have in common?

M.Choice: They both feel disappointment in a creation.

P.Choice: They both desire to create an object of beauty.

R.Choice: They both feel a sense of satisfaction about a creation.

S.Choice: They both desire to maintain a respectable reputation.

SubTopics: Determine a theme or central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Select TWO central ideas shared by BOTH passages.

A.Choice: The creators are selfishly unwilling to share their creations with others.

B.Choice: The process of creating can have unsettling results.

C.Choice: The process of creation is a solitary occupation.

E.Choice: The creators have an obsession with their creations.

F.Choice: The process of creation is more important than the creation itself.

SubTopics: Analyze how an author's ideas or claims are developed and refined by particular sentences, paragraphs, or larger portions of a text.
Content: The following item has two parts. Answer Part A and then answer Part B.
What is the relationship between paragraph 1 and paragraph 6 in the passage?

M.Choice: Both paragraphs describe the spirit embodied by the Pony Express riders.

P.Choice: Both paragraphs emphasize the speed and expertise of the riders.

R.Choice: Both paragraphs describe the excitement of citizens at both ends of the route.

S.Choice: Both paragraphs stress that the riders were experts at traveling on water as well as on land.

Content: Select one detail from EACH paragraph that supports the correct answer in Part A.

A.Choice: “A pause of seconds, and a cannon booms in the distance ...” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “The rider leaps to his saddle and starts.” (paragraph 1)

C.Choice: “A ferry boat under a full head of steam is waiting.” (paragraph 1)

D.Choice: “The crowd behind breaks into tumultuous applause.” (paragraph 1)

E.Choice: “... two most important towns in the far West, ...” (paragraph 6)

F.Choice: “... the first outgoing and incoming mails.” (paragraph 6)

H.Choice: “... the eastbound mail was placed on board a steamer at San Francisco and sent up the river ...” (paragraph 6)

J.Choice: “... accompanied by an enthusiastic delegation of business men.” (paragraph 6)

SubTopics: Analyze how an author presents and develops key ideas and events to impact meaning.
Content: How does the author present information in the passage?

M.Choice: The author begins by explaining general ideas then gives additional specific details.

P.Choice: The author lists the least important ideas first then concludes with the most important ideas.

R.Choice: The author describes the reaction geographically, starting in the east and moving to the west.

S.Choice: The author gives the history chronologically from the first event that occurred to the final celebration.

Topics: Reading Information - Integration Of Knowledge & Ideas
SubTopics: Evaluate how reasoning and evidence affects the argument and specific claims in a text.
Content: What are TWO claims presented at the beginning of the passage?

A.Choice: “The rider leaps to his saddle and starts. In less than a minute he is at the post office where the letter pouch, square in shape with four padlocked pockets, is awaiting him.” (paragraph 1)

B.Choice: “A ferry boat under a full head of steam is waiting. With scarcely checked speed, the horse thunders onto the deck of the craft.” (paragraph 1)

C.Choice: “Some scream themselves hoarse; others are strangely silent; and some —  strong men — are moved to tears ...” (paragraph 1)

D.Choice: “The managers of the Central Overland, California and Pike's Peak Express Company had laid their plans well.” (paragraph 2)

SubTopics: Determine a central idea of a text and analyze its development; provide an objective or critical summary.
Content: Which sentence BEST expresses a central idea of the passage?

M.Choice: The Pony Express was the first mail delivery system in the United States.

P.Choice: The Pony Express, despite meeting with some early criticism, became a showcase for American ingenuity.

R.Choice: The Pony Express, despite the dangers its riders faced, was welcomed by the people of the West as an important addition to their lives.

S.Choice: The Pony Express was a contributing factor in the increasingly poor relations between Western settlers and Plains Indians.

M.Choice: Paragraph 4 gives supporting details to explain why many Californians planned to use the Pony Express.
